# Accessibility Audit Playbook

Structure: **WCAG criteria × pages.** Walk each page in scope, apply WCAG checks, record failures.

Based on [WCAG 2.2](https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/) at Level AA.

---

## When to run

- Compliance cadence (quarterly or per regulatory requirement)
- Before a feature ships that significantly changes interaction
- After UX refresh — styles may have broken contrast or focus states
- When procuring a third-party component library — vet before adoption

---

## Preparation

1. List pages in scope (top traffic, critical flows: sign-up, checkout, core app).
2. Tools: axe DevTools (or similar automated scanner), screen reader (VoiceOver / NVDA / JAWS), keyboard-only session.
3. Assistive tech simulators: forced-colors mode, reduced motion, 200% zoom, screen magnifier.
4. Read the [accesslint:reviewer skill](../../accesslint-reviewer/) if available for deeper audits.

---

## WCAG Level A + AA checks

### 1. Perceivable

- [ ] **1.1.1 Non-text content** — every image has `alt` (decorative: `alt=""`); icons have label or `aria-label`
- [ ] **1.2.1 Audio-only / video-only** — transcripts provided
- [ ] **1.2.2 Captions** — videos with audio have captions
- [ ] **1.3.1 Info and relationships** — heading hierarchy correct (single h1, no level skip); landmarks used
- [ ] **1.3.2 Meaningful sequence** — DOM order matches visual order
- [ ] **1.3.5 Input purpose** — autocomplete attributes on common inputs (email, name, tel)
- [ ] **1.4.1 Use of color** — color is never the only means of conveying info
- [ ] **1.4.3 Contrast (minimum)** — normal text ≥ 4.5:1, large text ≥ 3:1 (see accesslint:contrast-checker)
- [ ] **1.4.4 Resize text** — usable at 200% browser zoom without horizontal scroll
- [ ] **1.4.10 Reflow** — content reflows at 320 CSS pixels (no horizontal scroll)
- [ ] **1.4.11 Non-text contrast** — UI components and graphics ≥ 3:1
- [ ] **1.4.12 Text spacing** — usable when line-height / letter / word spacing increased
- [ ] **1.4.13 Content on hover or focus** — dismissible, hoverable, persistent

### 2. Operable

- [ ] **2.1.1 Keyboard** — all functionality via keyboard (no mouse-only)
- [ ] **2.1.2 No keyboard trap** — can always leave a component
- [ ] **2.4.1 Bypass blocks** — skip-to-main-content link present
- [ ] **2.4.2 Page titled** — unique, descriptive `<title>` per page
- [ ] **2.4.3 Focus order** — tab order matches visual/logical order
- [ ] **2.4.4 Link purpose** — link text describes destination (no "click here" / "read more") — see accesslint:link-purpose
- [ ] **2.4.7 Focus visible** — visible focus indicator on every focusable element
- [ ] **2.5.3 Label in name** — visible label text is in the accessible name
- [ ] **2.5.8 Target size (minimum)** — interactive targets ≥ 24×24 CSS pixels (exceptions documented)

### 3. Understandable

- [ ] **3.1.1 Language of page** — `<html lang>` correct
- [ ] **3.2.1 On focus** — focusing an element doesn't cause unexpected context change
- [ ] **3.2.2 On input** — changing a value doesn't cause unexpected context change
- [ ] **3.3.1 Error identification** — errors clearly identified in text
- [ ] **3.3.2 Labels or instructions** — every input has a visible label or instruction
- [ ] **3.3.3 Error suggestion** — form errors suggest how to fix
- [ ] **3.3.4 Error prevention** — for legal/financial: confirm, review, undo

### 4. Robust

- [ ] **4.1.2 Name, role, value** — every custom component has correct ARIA role + accessible name
- [ ] **4.1.3 Status messages** — toasts/alerts use `aria-live` or equivalent

---

## Manual assistive technology sweep

On critical flows (sign-up, checkout), with keyboard only and with screen reader:

- [ ] Can complete the flow end-to-end?
- [ ] Are errors announced?
- [ ] Is loading state announced?
- [ ] Is the focus managed on navigation (SPA moves focus to new page's h1)?

---

## Recording findings

Each failure becomes a row in `../INVENTORY.md`:

```
| A11Y-<WCAG>-<N> | bug | <page> | <WCAG criterion>: <summary> | open | P<N> | {{DATE}} | {{DATE}} | {{DATE}} | — |
```

**Severity guide:**
- **P0** — blocks a user group entirely (e.g., screen reader user can't complete sign-up)
- **P1** — degrades experience significantly (missing labels, broken focus order)
- **P2** — polish (contrast borderline, target size below minimum on non-critical)
- **P3** — best-practice deviation with no known user impact

---

## Output artifacts

- `index.md` — run context, scope (pages), tools used, assistive tech versions
- `findings.md` — grouped by WCAG principle
- Optional: `reports/axe-<page>.json` — raw axe results
- Optional: `evidence/<id>.md` — screenshots or screen-reader transcripts

---

## Tips

- **Automated scans catch ~30%.** The rest needs manual testing. Budget time for it.
- **Involve real users** with disabilities if at all possible — they catch what simulators miss.
- **Don't wait for compliance deadline.** Accessibility debt compounds.
- **Celebrate when you fix P0/P1 categories.** Visible progress motivates.
